{{Redirect3|First-move advantage|For the business term, see [[First-mover advantage]]}}
{{chess notation}}
[[Image:Wilhelm Steinitz2.jpg|right|thumb|alt=A man with full length beard wearing a three piece suit.|[[Wilhelm Steinitz]], who in 1889 claimed chess is a draw with best play]]

The '''first-move advantage in chess''' is the inherent advantage of the player (called [[White and Black in chess|White]]) who makes the first move in [[chess]]. Chess players and [[Chess theory|theorists]] generally agree that White begins the game with some advantage. [[Statistics]] compiled since 1851 support this view, showing that White consistently [[List of chess terms#Win|wins]] slightly more often than [[White and Black in chess|Black]], usually scoring between 52 and 56&nbsp;percent. White's [[List of chess terms#Winning percentage|winning percentage]]<ref>
White's overall winning percentage is calculated by taking the percentage of games won by White plus half the percentage of drawn games. Thus, if out of 100&nbsp;games White wins 40, draws 32, and loses 28, White's total winning percentage is 40 plus half of 32, i.e. 56&nbsp;percent.</ref> is about the same for [[tournament]] games between humans and games between [[computer]]s. However, White's advantage is less significant in [[Fast chess|rapid]] games and in games between weaker players.

Chess players and [[Chess theory|theoreticians]] have long debated whether, given [[Solved game#Perfect play|perfect play]] by both sides, the game should end in a win for White, or a [[draw (chess)|draw]]. <!-- Note to other editors: I have been unable to find any reliable sources for views of leading players before Steinitz. Jerzy Gizycki claims that "Philidor thought ... that whoever made first move and made no mistake would win." Jerzy Gizycki, A History of Chess, The Abbey Library, 1977, p. 106. ISBN 07196-0086-3. However, I have Philidor's book and can't find anything like this. Can anyone find a reliable source for this? --> Since at least 1889, when [[World Chess Championship|World Champion]] [[Wilhelm Steinitz]] addressed the issue, the overwhelming consensus has been that a perfectly played game would end in a draw. However, a few notable players have argued that White's advantage may be sufficient to force a win: [[Weaver Adams]] and [[Vsevolod Rauzer]] claimed that White is winning after the first move 1.e4, while [[Hans Berliner]] argued that 1.d4 may win for White. It is possible that computers will eventually resolve the debate by determining the correct outcome of a perfectly played game of chess, as they have for [[checkers]].

Some players, including World Champions [[Jos<U+00E9> Ra<U+00FA>l Capablanca]], [[Emanuel Lasker]], and [[Bobby Fischer]], have expressed fears of a "draw death" as chess becomes more deeply analyzed. To alleviate this danger, Capablanca and Fischer both proposed [[chess variant]]s to renew interest in the game, while Lasker suggested changing how draws and [[stalemate]] are scored.

Since 1988, chess theorists have challenged previously well-established views about White's advantage. [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]] (GM) [[Andr<U+00E1>s Adorj<U+00E1>n]] wrote a series of books on the theme that "Black is OK!", arguing that the general perception that White has an advantage is founded more in [[psychology]] than reality. GM [[Mihai Suba]] and others contend that sometimes White's [[List of chess terms#Initiative|initiative]] disappears for no apparent reason as a game progresses. The prevalent style of play for Black today is to seek [[List of chess terms#Dynamism|dynamic]], unbalanced positions with active [[List of chess terms#Counterplay|counterplay]], rather than merely trying to [[List of chess terms#Equalise/Equalize|equalize]].

Modern writers also argue that Black has certain countervailing advantages. The consensus that White should try to win can be a psychological burden for the White player, who sometimes loses by trying too hard to win. Moreover, according to [[game theory]], playing second may be advantageous because White has to reveal his hand first. Some openings are thus considered good for Black but less so for White, because White's extra [[Tempo (chess)|tempo]] allows Black to adjust in advance to the opponent's plans. Some symmetrical openings (i.e. those where both players make the same moves) can also lead to situations where moving first is a disadvantage, either for psychological or objective reasons.

