| |pl| | | | |qd|pl|=
| |bl| | | | |bl| |=
|rl| | | | |rl| |kl|=
|Polugaevsky <U+2013> Ft<U+00E1><U+010D>nik, position after 28.Rf1
}}

[[Lev Polugaevsky]]-[[<U+013D>ubom<U+00ED>r Ft<U+00E1><U+010D>nik]], [[Lucerne]] [[Chess Olympiad|Olympiad]] 1982:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1045547 | title=Lev Polugaevsky vs <U+013D>ubom<U+00ED>r Ft<U+00E1><U+010D>nik (1982) | publisher=ChessGames.com | accessdate=2008-06-28 }}</ref> '''1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Rd1 a6 10. b3 Nbd7 11. e4 Qb8 12. Bb2 O-O''' Suba wrote of a similar Hedgehog position, "White's position looks ideal. That's the naked truth about it, but the 'ideal' has by definition one drawback<U+2014>it cannot be improved."<ref>Suba 1991, p. 20.</ref> '''13. Nd2 Rd8 14. a4 Qc7 15. Qe3 Rac8 16. Qe2 Ne5 17. h3?''' According to Ft<U+00E1><U+010D>nik, 17.f4 Neg4 18.Rf1 is better. '''h5! 18. f4 Ng6 19. Nf3''' Now Black breaks open the position in typical Hedgehog fashion. '''d5! 20. cxd5?!''' Ft<U+00E1><U+010D>nik considers 20.e5 or 20.exd5 preferable. '''h4! 21. Nxh4 Nxh4 22. gxh4 Qxf4 23. dxe6 fxe6 24. e5?''' Ft<U+00E1><U+010D>nik recommends instead 24.Rxd8 Rxd8 25.Rd1. '''Bc5+ 25. Kh1 Nh5! 26. Qxh5 Qg3 27. Nd5''' Other moves get [[checkmate|mated]] immediately: 27.Bxb7 Qh3#; 27.Qe2 Qxh3#; 27.Qg4 Bxg2#. '''Rxd5 28. Rf1 Qxg2+! 29. Kxg2 Rd2+''' If 30.Kg3 (the only legal response to the [[double check]]), Rg2+ 31.Kf4 Rf8+ forces mate. [[List of chess terms#Resign|0<U+2013>1]]<ref>Notes by Ft<U+00E1><U+010D>nik from ''[[Chess Informant]]'', Volume 35, <U+0160>ahovski Informator, 1983, p. 35 (Game 50). This was voted the second-best game of the 724 games in Volume 35. ''Chess Informant'', Volume 36, <U+0160>ahovski Informator, 1984, p. 6.</ref>

An examination of reversed and symmetrical openings illustrates White's and Black's respective advantages:
{{clear}}

=====Reversed openings=====
In a "reversed opening", White plays an opening typically played by Black, but with colors reversed and thus an extra [[tempo (chess)|tempo]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Brace, E. | title=An Illustrated Dictionary of Chess | publisher=David McKay | year=1977 | page=143 | id=ISBN 0-89058-020-0 }}</ref><ref>Hooper and Whyld 1992, p. 339.</ref> Evans writes of such openings, "If a defense is considered good for Black, it must be even better for White with a move in hand."<ref>{{cite book | author=Evans, L. | title=The Chess Opening for You | publisher=R.H.M. Press | year=1975 | page=38 | id=ISBN 0-89058-020-0 }} Lasker acknowledges this idea, without actually adopting it, writing, "Since the Sicilian yields a fair game to the second player, one is tempted to think that it should be proportionately stronger when essayed by the first player, who has all the advantages of that Opening and a move into the bargain." Lasker 1960, p. 99.</ref> Former World Champion [[Mikhail Botvinnik]] reportedly expressed the same view.<ref>IMs Alexander Raetsky and Maxim Chetverik relate "an old anecdote" that, "In the [[Moscow]] Chess Club someone answered 1.c4 with 1...e5 and was immediately reprimanded by former World Champion Mikhail Botvinnik. Botvinnik carefully explained that White now had a Sicilian with a tempo more..." {{cite book | author=Raetsky, A. & Chetverik, M. | title=English ...e5 | publisher=Everyman Chess | year=2003 | page=5 | id=ISBN 1-85744-339-X }}</ref><ref>GM [[Bent Larsen]] recalled playing a [[List of chess terms#Blitz chess|blitz game]] where Bovinnik [[List of chess terms#Kibitz|kibitzed]] after 1.c4 e5 that Black should take his move back because the "Sicilian is so strong that you cannot let your opponent play it with an extra tempo." Andrew Soltis, "Chess to Enjoy" column, "KIBITZER: ''one who gives good advice to your opponent''", ''[[Chess Life]]'', May 1995, p. 18.</ref> Watson questions this idea, citing Suba's thesis that Black, by moving second, has more complete information than White.<ref name="Watson 1998_p231"/> He writes, "everyone has such difficulties playing as White against a Sicilian Defence (1.e4 c5), but ... leading masters have no qualms about answering 1.c4 with 1...e5."<ref name="Watson 1998_page233">Watson 1998, p. 233.</ref> To explain this [[paradox]], Watson discusses several different reversed Sicilian lines, showing how Black can exploit the disadvantages of various "extra" moves for White.<ref>Watson 1998, pp. 234<U+2013>36.</ref> He concludes, "The point is, Black's set-up in the Sicilian is fine as a reactive system, but not worth much when trying to claim the initiative as White. This is true because Black is able to react to the specific plan White chooses; in Suba's terms, his information is indeed a move greater! Furthermore, he is able to take advantage of dead equal positions which White (hoping to retain the advantage of the first move) would normally avoid."<ref>Watson 1998, p. 236. In an earlier book, Watson wrote of the position after 1.c4 e5, "More often than not, the extra tempo brings with it the drawback of committing oneself before one's opponent, and thus opening oneself to possible counterattacks and equalizing plans."
{{cite book | author=Watson, J. | title=English 1...P-K4 | publisher=B. T. Batsford | year=1979 | page=ix | id=ISBN 978-0713420852 }}</ref>
[[Image:Vladimir Malaniuk 2009.jpg|thumb|right|"That extra move's gonna hurt me." <U+2014> [[Vladimir Malaniuk]]]]

Watson also observes, "Similarly, the [[Dutch Defence]] looks particularly sterile when White achieves the reversed positions a tempo up (it turns out that he has nothing useful to do!); and indeed, many standard Black openings are not very inspiring when one gets them as White, tempo in hand."<ref name="Watson 1998_page233"/> GM [[Alex Yermolinsky]] likewise notes that GM [[Vladimir Malaniuk]], a successful exponent of the [[Dutch Defense|Leningrad Dutch]] (1.d4 f5 2.g3 g6) at the highest levels,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1070347 | title=Kasparov-Malaniuk, Moscow 1988 | publisher=ChessGames.com | accessdate=2008-06-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1334325 | title=Karpov-Malaniuk, Keres Memorial rapid 2005 | publisher=ChessGames.com | accessdate=2008-06-28 }}</ref> "once made a deep impression on me by casually dismissing someone's suggestion that he should try 1.f4 as White. He smiled and said, 'That extra move's gonna hurt me.'&nbsp;"<ref>{{cite book | author=[[Alex Yermolinsky|Yermolinsky, A.]] | title=The Road to Chess Improvement | publisher=Gambit Publications | year=1999 | page=149 | id=ISBN 1-901983-24-2 }}</ref>

Yermolinsky also agrees with [[Alexander Alekhine|Alekhine's]] criticism of 1.g3 e5 2.Nf3,<ref>{{cite book | author=[[Alexander Alekhine|Alekhine, A.]] | title=Alexander Alekhine's Best Games | publisher=Henry Holt and Company | year=1996 | page=100 | id=ISBN 0-8050-4723-9 }};{{cite book | author=[[Alexander Alekhine|Alekhine, A.]] | title=My Best Games of Chess 1924<U+2013>1937 | publisher=David McKay | year=1965 | pages=10<U+2013>11 | id=ISBN 978-0679140245 }}</ref> a reversed [[Alekhine's Defense]], in [[Richard R<U+00E9>ti|R<U+00E9>ti]]-Alekhine, [[Baden-Baden]] 1925,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1012326 | title=R<U+00E9>ti-Alekhine, Baden-Baden 1925 | publisher=ChessGames.com | accessdate=2008-06-28 }}</ref> writing that Alekhine "understood the difference in opening philosophies for White and Black, and realized they just can't be the same! White is supposed to try for more than just obtaining a comfortable game in reversed colour opening set-ups, and, as the statistics show<U+2014>surprisingly for a lot of people, but not for me<U+2014>White doesn't even score as well as Black does in the same positions with his extra tempo and all."<ref>{{cite book | author=[[Alex Yermolinsky|Yermolinsky, A.]] | title=The Road to Chess Improvement | publisher=Gambit Publications | year=1999 | page=149 | id=ISBN 1-901983-24-2 }} Watson cites another example of an unsuccessful reversed opening for White: while the Meran Variation of the [[Semi-Slav Defense]] is considered a dynamic counterattacking system, with colors reversed it is the classical variation of the [[Colle System]], one of the dullest [[Queen's Pawn Game|queen-pawn openings]].{{cite book | author=[[John L. Watson|Watson, John]] | title=Mastering the Chess Openings, Volume 2 | publisher=Gambit Publications | year=2007 | page=101 | id=ISBN 978-1-904600-69-5 }}</ref> [[Howard Staunton]], generally considered to have been the strongest player in the world from 1843 to 1851,<ref>{{cite book | author=[[Raymond Keene|Keene, R.]] and Coles, R.N. | title=Howard Staunton - The English World Chess Champion | publisher=British Chess Magazine | year=1975 | page=1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author=[[Andrew Soltis|Soltis, A.]] | title=The Great Chess Tournaments and Their Stories | publisher=Chilton Book Company | year=1975 | pages=2, 20 | id=ISBN 0-8019-6138-6 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author=[[Israel Horowitz|Horowitz, I.A.]] | title=The World Chess Championship - A History | publisher=Macmillan | year=1973 | pages=3<U+2013>4 | id={{LCCN|72|0|80175}}, {{OCLC|604994}}
}}</ref> made a similar point over 160 years ago, writing that [[Owen's Defense]] (1.e4 b6) is playable for Black, but that 1.b3 is inferior to "the more customary [first] moves, from its being essentially defensive".<ref>{{cite book | author=[[Howard Staunton|Staunton, H.]] | title=The Chess-Player's Handbook | publisher=George Bell & Sons | year=1847 | page=379 }}</ref>

Watson concludes that (a) "most moves have disadvantages as well as advantages, so an extra move is not always an unqualified blessing"; (b) "with his extra information about what White is doing, Black can better react to the new situation"; and (c) because a draw is likely to be more acceptable to Black than to White, White is apt to avoid lines that allow drawish simplifications, while Black may not object to such lines.<ref name="Watson 1998_page233"/>

=====Symmetrical openings=====
Rowson writes that "in general one would assume that whatever advantage White has would be revealed most clearly in [[Symmetry|symmetrical]] positions."<ref>Rowson 2005, p. 230.</ref> Accordingly, Watson, Suba, Evans, and the eminent player and theorist [[Aron Nimzowitsch]] (1886<U+2013>1935) have all argued that it is in Black's interest to avoid symmetry.<ref>Watson 1998, pp. 236<U+2013>37.</ref><ref>Suba contends that Black should strive for "[e]lastic and non-symmetrical pawn structures." Suba 1991, p. 24.</ref><ref>"To win with the Black pieces you must assume risks and avoid symmetrical positions." Evans 1970, p. 21.</ref><ref>Nimzowitsch asserted that if in the symmetrical [[French Defence#Exchange Variation: 3.exd5 exd5|Exchange Variation]] of the [[French Defence|French Defense]] White develops his [[List of chess terms#Kingside|king's]] [[knight (chess)|knight]] to f3, that "must be answered" by ...Ne7, while ...Nf6 "is the necessary answer" if White develops the knight to e2.
{{cite book
 | author=[[Aron Nimzowitsch|Nimzowitsch, A.]]
 | title=Chess Praxis (21st Century Edition)
 | publisher=Hays Publishing
 | year=1993
 | page=217
 | ISBN=1-880673-91-6
}} {{cite book
 | author=[[Aron Nimzowitsch|Nimzowitsch, A.]]
 | title=Chess Praxis: The Praxis of My System
 | publisher=Dover Publications
 | year=1962
 | page=299
 | ISBN=978-0486202969
}}</ref> Nonetheless, even symmetrical opening lines sometimes illustrate the tenuous nature of White's advantage, in several respects.

It is often difficult for White to prove an advantage in symmetrical opening lines. As GM [[Bent Larsen]] wrote, annotating a game that began 1.c4 c5 2.b3 b6,<ref>{{cite web
 | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1106955
 | title=Petrosian <U+2013> Saidy, San Antonio 1972
 | publisher=ChessGames.com
 | accessdate=2008-06-28
}}</ref> "In symmetrical openings, White has a theoretical advantage, but in many of them it is only theoretical."<ref>{{cite book
 | author=[[Bent Larsen|Larsen, B.]]
 | coauthors=[[David Levy (chess player)|Levy, D.]]
 | title=San Antonio 1972
 | publisher=RHM Chess Publishing
 | year=1973
 | page=201
 | id=ASIN B000O641VO
}}</ref> GM [[Andrew Soltis]] wrote in 2008 that he hates playing against the symmetrical [[Petroff's Defense]] (1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nf6), and accordingly varies with 2.Nc3, the [[Vienna Game]].<ref name="Soltis_2008_p10-11">{{cite news
 | title=Going Ape
 | author=[[Andrew Soltis|Soltis, A.]]
 | work=Chess Life
 | date=February 2008
 | pages=10<U+2013>11
}}</ref> However, there too he has been unable to find a way to an advantage after the symmetrical 2...Nc6 3.g3<ref>White can play more aggressively with 3.Bc4 Bc5 4.Qg4, when the symmetrical 4...Qg5?? would lose Black's [[queen (chess)|queen]], and the natural 4...Qf6? is strongly met by 5.Nd5! Qxf2+ 6.Kd1 Kf8 7.Nh3 Qd4 8.d3 Bb6 9.Qf3 (de Firmian 2008, p. 119). However, Black can break the symmetry with 3...Nf6 4. Nf3 Nxe4! 5.Nxe4 d5 (de Firmian 2008, p. 40) or, after 4.d3, either 4...Bb4 (de Firmian 2008, p. 115) or 4...Na5 (Kaufman 2004, pp. 368<U+2013>72).</ref> g6 4.Bg2 Bg7, or after 3.Nf3 Nf6 ([[List of chess terms#Transposition|transposing]] to the [[Four Knights Game]]) 4.Bb5 Bb4<ref>Alternatively, Black can break the symmetry with either the [[List of chess terms#Sharp|sharp]] 4...Nd4, the [[Akiba Rubinstein|Rubinstein]] Variation, which GM de Firmian considers "Black's best winning attempt" (de Firmian 2008, pp. 121<U+2013>22), or the bizarre-looking but solid 4...Bd6!?, which avoids White's threat to win a pawn with Bxc6 followed by Nxe5, and prepares ...0-0, possibly followed by ...Re8 and ...Bf8, or by ...b6 and ...Bb7 (Kaufman 2004, pp. 339<U+2013>40).</ref> 5.0-0 0-0 6.d3 d6 7.Bg5 Bg4 8.Nd5<ref>According to de Firmian, 8.Bxf6 gxf6 9.Nd5 favors White (de Firmian 2008, p. 123).</ref> Nd4 9.Nxb4<ref>After 9.Bc4, Black successfully broke the symmetry with 9...Qd7 10.Bxf6 Bxf3 11.gxf3 Qh3 12.Ne7+ Kh8 13.Bxg7+ Kxg7 14.Nf5+ Nxf5 15.exf5 Kh8 [[Chess punctuation#.2B.E2.88.92 (.E2.88.92.2B): Decisive advantage|-+]] in Berman-[[Arthur Bisguier|Bisguier]], [[New York]], 1947. If 16.Kh1, Rg8 17.Rg1 Rxg1+ 18.Qxg1 Rg8 wins White's queen (Chernev 1955, pp. 162<U+2013>63).</ref> Nxb5, or 7.Ne2 Ne7 8.c3 Ba5 9.Ng3 c6 10.Ba4 Ng6 11.d4 d5, when 12.exd5[[Punctuation (chess)#.3F.21: Dubious move|?!]] e4[[Punctuation (chess)#.21: Good move|!]] may even favor Black.<ref name="Soltis_2008_p10-11"/>

Moreover, symmetrical positions may be disadvantageous to White in that he has to commit himself first.<ref>Rowson writes that GM [[Jonathan Speelman]] once joked "that the initial position was a decisive [[Zugzwang#Reciprocal zugzwang|reciprocal zugzwang]] and that White was losing. ... [L]ike all jokes it contained some interesting truth for the discerning person." Rowson 2005, p. 203.</ref><ref>Suba has observed, "Even the symmetrical variations of some openings present White with a critical moment at an early stage and he cannot progress without making concessions to Black." Suba 1991, p. 134.</ref> Watson notes that it is even difficult for White to play noncommittally in a symmetrical position, since almost every move has certain drawbacks.<ref>Watson writes of the Exchange Variation of the French Defense that, "It is actually difficult for White to even ''waste'' a move without effect, e.g. a3 or h3 will discourage him from [[castling]] on the wing where he has made that advance." Watson 1986, p. 28.</ref> Fischer once went so far as to claim that after '''1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 g6 3.Bg2 Bg7 4.0-0 0-0 5.d3 d6''' (Reinhard <U+2013> Fischer, Western Open 1963),<ref>{{cite web
 | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1044582
 | title=Reinhard <U+2013> Fischer, Western Open 1963
 | publisher=ChessGames.com
 | accessdate=2008-06-28
}}</ref> "&nbsp;'Believe it or not,' Black stands better! Now, whatever White does, Black will vary it and get an [[asymmetry|asymmetrical]] position and have the superior position due to his better [[pawn structure]]!"<ref>Donaldson 1999, p. 72 (based on Fischer's annotations in {{cite news
 | title=Fischer Talks Chess
 | author=[[Bobby Fischer|Fischer, Bobby]]
 | work=Chess Life
 | date=September 1963
 | pages=215<U+2013>17
}} Also available on DVD; includes Fischer's win as Black in a Queen's Gambit Declined against Berliner.)</ref> However, GM [[Paul Keres]] responded in [[CHESS magazine|''CHESS'' magazine]], "We just don't believe it!"<ref>Donaldson 1999, p. 72.</ref> In symmetrical positions, as the [[Julian Hodgson|Hodgson]] <U+2013> [[Keith Arkell|Arkell]] and [[Lajos Portisch|Portisch]] <U+2013> [[Mikhail Tal|Tal]] games discussed below illustrate, Black can continue to imitate White as long as he finds it feasible and desirable to do so, and deviate when that ceases to be the case.

Further, a particular extra move is sometimes more of a liability than an asset. For example, Soltis notes that the [[French Defence#Exchange Variation: 3.exd5 exd5|Exchange French]] position arising after 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 exd5 4.Nf3 Nf6 "is pretty equal." The same position, but with Black's knight moved to e4, arises in Petroff's Defense after 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Nxe5 d6 4.Nf3 Nxe4 5.d4 d5. That position offers White better chances precisely because Black's extra move (...Ne4) allows the advanced knight to become a target for attack.<ref>{{cite news
 | title=Gauging Progress
 | author=[[Andrew Soltis|Soltis, A.]]
 | work=Chess Life
 | date=July 2005
 | page=25
}}</ref><ref>{{cite book
 | author=[[Vassilios Kotronias|Kotronias, V.]] 
 | coauthors=Tzermiadianos, A.
 | title=Beating the Petroff
 | publisher=Batsford
 | year=2004
 | page=11
 | ISBN=07134-8919-7
}}</ref>

Finally, symmetrical positions may be difficult for the White player for psychological reasons. Watson writes that anyone who tries the Exchange French, "even if he thinks he is playing for a win, assume[s] a psychological burden. White has already ceded the advantage of the first move, and knows it, whereas Black is challenged to find ways to seize the initiative."<ref>Watson 1986, p. 29.</ref> Two famous examples of White losses in the Exchange French are [[Mikhail Gurevich (chess player)|M. Gurevich]] <U+2013> [[Nigel Short|Short]] and Tatai <U+2013> [[Viktor Korchnoi|Korchnoi]].<ref>{{cite web
 | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1124451
 | title=Mikhail Gurevich  <U+2013> Nigel Short, Manila Interzonal 1990
 | publisher=ChessGames.com
 | accessdate=2008-06-28
}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
 | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1082469
 | title=Stefano Tatai <U+2013> Viktor Korchnoi, Beer Sheva 1978
 | publisher=ChessGames.com
 | accessdate=2008-06-28
}}</ref> In M. Gurevich-Short, a game between two of the world's leading players,<ref>The [[FIDE]] International Rating List issued on July 1, 1990 ranked the top active players in the world as follows (by Elo rating): 1. Kasparov 2800; 2. Karpov 2730; 3<U+2013>4. [[Boris Gelfand|Gelfand]], [[Vassily Ivanchuk|Ivanchuk]] 2680; 5. [[Jan Timman|Timman]] 2660; 6<U+2013>7. [[Jaan Ehlvest|Ehlvest]], [[Valery Salov|Salov]] 2655; 8. [[Mikhail Gurevich (chess player)|M. Gurevich]] 2640; 9. [[Yasser Seirawan|Seirawan]] 2635; 10<U+2013>12. [[Ulf Andersson|Andersson]], Korchnoi, [[Rafael Vaganian|Vaganian]] 2630; 13<U+2013>15. [[Sergey Dolmatov|Dolmatov]], [[Alexey Dreev|Dreev]], [[Alexander Khalifman|Khalifman]] 2615; '''16<U+2013>20.''' [[Viswanathan Anand|Anand]], [[John Nunn|Nunn]], [[Lev Polugaevsky|Polugaevsky]], [[Zoltan Ribli|Ribli]], [[Nigel Short|Short]] 2610. ''Chess Informant'', Volume 49, <U+0160>ahovski Informator, 1990, pp. 426<U+2013>58.</ref> White needed only a draw to qualify for the [[Candidates Matches]], while Black needed to win.<ref>Aagaard 2004, p. 139.</ref> Gurevich played passively and was outplayed by Short, who achieved the necessary win, qualified for the Candidates, and ultimately [[Nigel Short#World Championship candidate|went on to challenge Kasparov for the World Championship]].<ref>Aagaard 2004, pp. 139<U+2013>42.</ref> In Tatai-Korchnoi, the [[Italy|Italian]] IM fell victim to Korchnoi's whirlwind [[List of chess terms#Mating attack|mating attack]], losing in just 14 moves.

